snippet.textDisplay:
I don't believe the earth is flat. Though I will say, the point about ships sailing over the horizon is kind of a valid arguement.. Since 79% of the earth is made up of water and the surface of water should always find level..

Then, just for a second, my mind went off with the fairies and thought 79% of the earth should be flat..
But that's when I came back down to earth, because GRAVITY... ... it just gave me that flat-footed perspective that I needed..

Though what if our feet were 100% flat and had to be at true level at all time, you would only be able to walk about 5kms from a 6 foot tall friend, that's still standing at the spot you started your 5km perfectly level hike, until you started walking off the surface of the earth, from your friends perspective, of course.

After all that, you think.. What if gravity is only relative for 5km from our perspective, then, everything beyond that point (clouds, light, sunset, your friend who walked off the earth surface) is not truly where we perceive it to be...
Or maybe it's all just irrelevant cause we live in a simulation.. and the creator (that cannot possibly all powerful) generated a theory called 'the 5km theory of irrelevantivity'..

OK.. I'll stop now 🤔💢🤯💢😴🤐

snippet.textDisplay:
Instead of the long argument, a simpler argument to shut up any flat earther would be, "Let's assume that NASA and all the other scientists are lying to us about round earth. Humans being born naturally curious would still spend the same amount of money if not more to explore "flat Earth" and what lies beyond it . So NASA is literally getting no extra cash for lying about the shape of earth but instead risking leaking of confidential files, and if leaked, it would be a huge loss. Tldr: high risk no reward. Absolutely unfeasible for anyone. So why would they do that?"

People are already set up by a mindset can't be approached with graphs, maths and facts. They have to be dealt with psychologically"
